{
  "text": "The recent development of a novel molecular imaging tool based on the detection of Cerenkov radiation (CR) by beta particles allows tracking of the bio-distribution of beta-emitters and their uptake within tumor parenchyma in vivo [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . It has been shown that Cerenkov luminescence imaging (CLI) can be used to measure the bio-distribution of beta plus [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] and beta minus emitters [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] . This suggests that 32 P-ATP can be considered as a novel theranostic radiopharmaceutical providing measurements of physiological proprieties of tumors (on the basis of its tumor-specific uptake) while inhibiting their growth and progression.",
